<task id="100" project="spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r6">
  <metadata>
    <title>D-H-00 Handler Infrastructure + Registration Pattern (Gate for Wave 1 + Wave 2)</title>
    <phase>Parallel — 8 Typed Tool Handlers</phase>
    <status>not-started</status>
    <estimated-effort>6 hours</estimated-effort>
    <dependencies>006, 009</dependencies>
    <blocks>101, 102, 103, 104, 105, 106, 107, 108, 109</blocks>
    <tags>bff-api, ai, refactoring, handler</tags>
    <rigor-hint>FULL</rigor-hint>
    <rigor-reason>Foundational handler infrastructure — registration pattern + base class wiring + test fixture pattern that gates all 8 typed handler tasks (Wave 1 + Wave 2) + dispatch tests. Documents contract every typed handler must follow.</rigor-reason>
    <parallel-group>H-G0</parallel-group>
    <parallel-safe>false</parallel-safe>
    <parallel-reason>Gates Wave 1 (101-104) and Wave 2 (105-108). No other handler task can begin until this lands.</parallel-reason>
  </metadata>

  <prompt>
    Land the shared handler infrastructure that the 8 typed tool handlers (FR-13 through
    FR-20) rest on. This task documents and codifies the contract every typed handler
    must satisfy: implements `IToolHandler` (renamed in Phase A task 006); registered
    via auto-discovery (no manual DI per handler — ADR-010 module pattern); has a
    corresponding `sprk_analysistool` Dataverse row with `sprk_handlerclass` field set
    to the C# class name for runtime discovery; ships a reusable unit-test fixture for
    handler tests so each Wave 1/Wave 2 task can lean on identical scaffolding.

    Concretely this task delivers: (a) a `HandlerRegistrationConventions.md` short doc
    in `Services/Ai/Handlers/` (or equivalent) that codifies the 4-point handler contract
    with worked example; (b) verification that the existing auto-discovery in
    `AnalysisServicesModule.cs` correctly picks up all `IToolHandler` implementations from
    the assembly (no per-handler DI line additions allowed); (c) the
    `TypedToolHandlerTestFixture` base class in `tests/unit/Sprk.Bff.Api.Tests/Services/Ai/Handlers/`
    with shared mocks (`IOpenAiClient`, `IScopeResolverService`, `ToolExecutionContext`
    + `ChatInvocationContext` builders, telemetry assertions per ADR-015); (d) a checked-in
    "contract test" template each handler task copies — verifies handler is registered,
    is discoverable by `sprk_handlerclass` lookup, exposes valid metadata.

    The infrastructure ships with ZERO new top-level Program.cs lines and ZERO new DI
    services registered outside `AnalysisServicesModule` per ADR-010. BFF publish-size
    delta MUST be measured and reported; expected ≤+0.2 MB (test infrastructure does not
    ship in production binary; only the doc + verifier do).
  </prompt>

  <role>
    Senior BFF engineer with .NET 8 + assembly auto-discovery experience. Familiar with
    `IAnalysisToolHandler` registration in `AnalysisServicesModule`, the `sprk_analysistool`
    Dataverse data model, and xUnit fixture patterns. Deep knowledge of ADR-010 DI
    minimalism and ADR-015 telemetry constraints.
  </role>

  <goal>
    Handler infrastructure landed: (1) `HandlerRegistrationConventions.md` documents the
    4-point contract with worked example; (2) auto-discovery verified — adding a new
    `IToolHandler` implementation to `Services/Ai/Handlers/` automatically registers
    without modifying DI module; (3) `TypedToolHandlerTestFixture` base class committed
    with shared mocks + context builders + telemetry assertion helpers; (4) "contract
    test" template that each Wave 1/Wave 2 task copies; (5) BFF publish-size verified
    ≤+0.2 MB; (6) `code-review` + `adr-check` both green. Downstream tasks 101–108 can
    proceed in parallel after this lands.
  </goal>

